- dashboards
- settings pages
- CRUD pages
- forms
- tables
- analytics blocks
- dialogs
- navigation
- cards
- empty states
- alerts
- filters

7. Derived component behavior
Include a section explaining how to derive components that do not exist in the original repo while preserving the source identity.
The AI must extend the source system conservatively instead of inventing a different style family.

8. Behavioral constraints
Explain what the AI must never do:
- introduce sharper geometry if the source uses a rounded language
- flatten or neutralize a spacious spacing character into a cramped generic admin style
- break spacing rhythm
- create inconsistent hierarchy
- use decorative elements without functional value
- overcomplicate interactions
- invent unsupported component patterns without grounding them in the source identity

9. UX reasoning rules
The AI must justify key layout and component decisions using:
- clarity
- hierarchy
- visual priority
- consistency
- task completion
- accessibility
- scalability

10. Output mode
The AI should:
- prefer product-ready UI
- reuse existing patterns
- extend the system instead of reinventing it
- preserve source design identity even across different UI categories
- generate components that feel native to the existing app's design language

11. Anti-drift rules
Add a dedicated section explaining how to avoid style drift when generating new screens over time.

12. Conservative adaptation rule
State explicitly that a portfolio, marketing page, or landing style can be adapted into dashboards or utility screens, but the defining traits of geometry, hierarchy, spacing, emphasis, and tone must remain recognizable.

